# StreamAssist Engineering Rules

These rules are the project-specific source of truth for AI-assisted work in StreamAssist. They apply to every task in this repository.

## 1. Project Mental Model

StreamAssist is a realtime interactive streaming platform:

- Frontend: Vue 3 + Vite in `apps/client`.
- Backend: Node.js / Express in `apps/server`.
- Realtime: WebSocket endpoints for call signaling and games.
- Media: mediasoup / WebRTC through `packages/call-core`.
- Product surfaces: Call, Mafia, Nadle, Nadraw Show, Checkers, Eat First, Coin Hub, overlays, OBS/viewer modes, Twitch chat integrations.

Current architecture has three client organization styles:

- Newer isolated slices in `apps/client/src/features/*`, currently `checkers` and `nadraw-show`.
- A large domain sub-app in `apps/client/src/eat-first`.
- Historical page/module domains such as `apps/client/src/nadle`, `apps/client/src/pages/NadleStreamPage.vue`, `apps/client/src/pages/MafiaPage.vue`, and shared `apps/client/src/components/call`.

Treat these as current architecture, not as permission to add more mixed layouts. New product work should default to isolated feature modules unless it intentionally extends an existing domain.

## 2. Complete Runtime Flow

Client startup:

- `apps/client/src/main.ts` preloads i18n, initializes `call-core` audio unlock, SEO metadata, analytics, Pinia, i18n, router, then mounts `App.vue`.
- `apps/client/src/App.vue` owns the global loader, runs `useAuth().refresh()` on mount, preloads landing clouds for visual routes, and renders `RouterView`.
- `apps/client/src/router.ts` defines the app shell under `/app`, route redirects, auth/admin guards, Eat First route guards, route-loading release behavior, and scroll behavior.
- `apps/client/src/layouts/AppShellLayout.vue` is the shell around `/app/*` routes.

Feature mounting:

- `/app/call` mounts `apps/client/src/components/call/CallPage.vue`.
- `/app/mafia` mounts `apps/client/src/pages/MafiaPage.vue`, which composes `CallPage.vue` with Mafia UI.
- `/app/nadle/:streamer` mounts `apps/client/src/pages/NadleStreamPage.vue`.
- `/app/nadraw-show/:streamer` mounts `apps/client/src/pages/NadrawShowPage.vue`.
- `/app/checkers/:roomId` mounts `apps/client/src/features/checkers/pages/CheckersPage.vue`.
- `/app/eat` mounts `apps/client/src/pages/EatFirstPage.vue`.
- `/app/admin/*` mounts `apps/client/src/admin/ui/*`.

Backend startup:

- `apps/server/src/index.ts` loads env, creates Express, CORS, cookie parser, JSON parser, mediasoup worker pool, `RoomManager`, five WebSocket servers, HTTP routes, `/health`, Twitch ingest, and shutdown handling.
- WebSocket upgrade paths are centralized in `apps/server/src/index.ts`: `/ws` or `/` for call signaling, `/nadle-ws`, `/eat-first-ws`, `/nadraw-show-ws`, and `/checkers-ws`.

Call join flow:

- `CallPage.vue` calls `useCallOrchestrator()` from `call-core`.
- `packages/call-core/src/useCallOrchestrator.ts` delegates to `useCallEngine`.
- `useCallEngine` opens signaling via `useRoomConnection`, sends `join-room`, waits for `room-state`, loads mediasoup `Device`, sets up receive path, then publishes local media only for `participant` role.
- Server signaling is handled by `apps/server/src/signaling/socketServer.ts` and `apps/server/src/signaling/messageHandlers.ts`.

State storage:

- Client auth state: `apps/client/src/composables/useAuth.ts`.
- Client call session state: `packages/call-core/src/stores/callSession.ts`.
- Client app stores: `apps/client/src/stores/*`.
- Eat First overlay session: `apps/client/src/eat-first/stores/eatOverlayMediasoupSession.js`.
- Server durable state: Prisma via `apps/server/src/prisma.ts`.
- Server ephemeral realtime state: `RoomManager`, `Room`, `Peer`, game socket maps, game stores.

## 3. Core Principles

- Preserve behavior unless the task explicitly asks for behavior changes.
- Prefer minimal, atomic diffs.
- Read related files and existing tests before editing.
- Reuse existing helpers, composables, stores, services, protocol constants, and packages.
- Do not invent APIs, message shapes, route contracts, or storage keys.
- Do not create duplicate sources of truth.
- Do not change WebRTC, mediasoup, reconnect, screen share, or teardown behavior unless explicitly requested.
- Do not hide behavior changes inside refactors.
- Prefer deleting duplicated code over layering more compatibility code.
- Keep UI strings, docs, comments, and test data in Ukrainian or English only; no Russian text.

## 4. Feature Architecture

Recommended feature template for new games or product modules:

```text
apps/client/src/features/<feature>/
  core/          # pure rules, types, deterministic helpers
  api/ or ws/    # transport wrapper and protocol constants
  orchestrator/  # use<Feature>Orchestrator()
  components/ or ui/
  pages/
```

Rules:

- Pure game rules belong in `core/` or `packages/*-core`, not in pages.
- Pages compose feature modules and render prepared state/actions.
- Components stay presentational unless they are explicitly feature containers.
- Shared UI belongs in `apps/client/src/components/ui` only when it is domain-agnostic.
- Shared call/media logic belongs in `packages/call-core`.
- Server game logic belongs beside its backend domain under `apps/server/src/<domain>`.
- New overlays should be isolated as feature/domain overlay layers, not mixed into call transport code.

Current feature review:

- Checkers: well-isolated engine/WS/orchestrator, but `CheckersPage.vue` is large and also wires `call-core` voice. Risk: medium-high.
- Nadraw Show: good orchestrator and feature folder; shares streamer context patterns with Nadle. Risk: medium.
- Eat First: deliberate sub-app in `eat-first`; JS-heavy, overlay/media path separate from main `CallPage`. Risk: medium.
- Nadle: historical page/module layout with a large page and composables. Risk: medium.
- Mafia: thin `MafiaPage.vue`, but heavy shared `CallPage.vue` integration. Risk: high.
- Coin Hub: clearer store/API/component boundary. Risk: low-medium.

## 5. Folder / Module Boundaries

Do:

- Import app-wide auth from `apps/client/src/composables/useAuth.ts`.
- Import API helpers from `apps/client/src/utils/apiFetch.ts`, `apiUrl.ts`, and `apiUrlPure.ts`.
- Import call APIs from `call-core` public exports.
- Keep `eat-first/index.ts` as a narrow public barrel for shell/pages.
- Use deep paths inside `eat-first` to avoid cycles.
- Keep server protocol constants beside their domain protocol files.

Do not:

- Import from another feature's internals for convenience.
- Expand barrels with internal-only exports.
- Import from a domain barrel inside that same domain when it can create cycles.
- Move game logic into `components/`.
- Move transport logic into overlays or UI components.
- Add app-wide stores for state that belongs only to one feature.

Needs verification before copying:

- Nadraw/Nadle shared streamer loading patterns.
- Eat First overlay mediasoup integration parity with main call flow.
- Any future migration from historical `pages/` layout to `features/`.

## 6. Orchestrator Pattern

Use `use<Feature>Orchestrator()` when a feature has WebSockets, timers, reconnects, server state, auth/role branching, host/viewer/player modes, overlays, or non-trivial derived state.

Current examples:

- `packages/call-core/src/useCallOrchestrator.ts`
- `apps/client/src/features/checkers/orchestrator/useCheckersOrchestrator.ts`
- `apps/client/src/features/nadraw-show/orchestrator/useNadrawShowOrchestrator.ts`
- `apps/client/src/eat-first/composables/control/useControlOrchestrator.js`

Rules:

- Pages should not own business logic.
- Orchestrators own side effects, cleanup, timers, reconnects, and stale socket guards.
- Orchestrators expose prepared state and actions.
- UI should not rebuild protocol maps, participant maps, or fallback chains.
- One trigger must cause one side effect.
- Every async action needs a pending/disposed/socket/room/revision/role guard.

## 7. Single Source of Truth Rules

Auth/user:

- SSOT: client `useAuth.ts`; server `apps/server/src/auth/*`, `session/sessionJwt.ts`, `session/me.ts`.
- Duplicate risks: manual role parsing, direct cookie/session parsing in feature code.
- Rule: UI uses `useAuth`; server authority uses signed httpOnly cookie and `resolvePrismaUserIdFromSession`.
- Cleanup candidate: repeated `isDatabaseConfigured()` helpers.
- Risk: high.

Streamer context:

- SSOT: server `nadle/streamerApiRouter.ts`, `auth/resolvePrismaUserFromSession.ts`, `nadraw-show/nadrawAccess.ts`; client `useNadleStreamerRoom`.
- Duplicate risks: Twitch username normalization and shared Nadle/Nadraw streamer lookup.
- Rule: resolve streamer ownership on the server.
- Cleanup candidate: shared username normalization helper.
- Risk: medium.

Rooms:

- SSOT: call rooms in `RoomManager`, `Room`, `Peer`; game rooms in each game store/socket.
- Duplicate risks: client-provided room IDs and local room state.
- Rule: server owns room membership and role authority.
- Cleanup candidate: protocol-level room validation tests.
- Risk: high.

Call/media state:

- SSOT: `packages/call-core`.
- Duplicate risks: Eat First overlay direct call-engine integration and feature-level media assumptions.
- Rule: do not duplicate produce/consume/reconnect/teardown/screen-share logic.
- Cleanup candidate: document Eat First overlay media invariants.
- Risk: high.

Participants/display names:

- SSOT: `call-core` helpers `buildCallParticipantMap`, `resolvePeerDisplayNameForUi`, `buildDisplayNameUiMap`, `normalizeDisplayName`.
- Duplicate risks: ad hoc display-name fallback chains.
- Rule: new UI must use call-core display helpers.
- Cleanup candidate: audit all user-visible call labels.
- Risk: medium.

Screen share:

- SSOT: `packages/call-core/src/screenShare/useCallScreenShare.ts`.
- Duplicate risks: separate start/stop/ended handling.
- Rule: never bypass screen-share serialization.
- Cleanup candidate: none without explicit task.
- Risk: high.

Remote audio/video tracks:

- SSOT: `useRemoteMedia.ts`, `StreamVideo.vue`, `StreamAudio.vue`, `ParticipantTile.vue`.
- Duplicate risks: clearing `srcObject`, remounting video, treating UI suppression as transport teardown.
- Rule: keep media element identity stable.
- Cleanup candidate: verify playback suppression runtime wiring.
- Risk: high.

Game state:

- Checkers: `features/checkers/core`, `packages/checkers-core`, server `checkersGameStore.ts`.
- Nadle: `packages/nadle-core`, client `nadle/`, server `nadle/gameStore.ts`.
- Nadraw: `features/nadraw-show`, server `nadrawGameStore.ts`.
- Eat First: client `eat-first/`, server `eatFirst/service.ts` and `snapshot.ts`.
- Mafia: `stores/mafiaGame.ts`, `stores/mafiaPlayers.ts`, server `Room` Mafia state.
- Rule: client may derive UI state, but server/game core owns authoritative rules.
- Risk: medium-high.

Leaderboard:

- SSOT: `apps/server/src/leaderboardRouter.ts`.
- Duplicate risks: client-posted results and repeated display/rating derivation.
- Rule: server must validate authenticated user, streamer scope, attempts, result, and game-specific authority.
- Cleanup candidate: contract/integration tests for writes.
- Risk: high.

Overlays:

- SSOT: Eat First overlay components/composables; Mafia overlay components; call media state from call-core.
- Duplicate risks: overlay-specific media maps and display names.
- Rule: overlays consume prepared state; they must not own media transport.
- Risk: medium-high.

Roles:

- SSOT: server auth/session/ownership checks, call `CallEngineRole`, Mafia host state in `Room`, Checkers roles in `checkersSocket.ts`.
- Duplicate risks: trusting client mode/role flags.
- Rule: client role flags are UI hints only; server decides authority.
- Risk: high.

WebSocket connection state:

- SSOT: each orchestrator/socket client owns its own status and reconnect timer.
- Duplicate risks: reconnect loops, stale sockets, duplicate subscriptions.
- Rule: close previous sockets, ignore stale sockets, clear timers on dispose.
- Risk: high.

